{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473589"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:10:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:10:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2523"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2523"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.03,0.13,0.28,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105724"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2523"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88190"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3711"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2411"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38494"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38496"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105724"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 11-year-old girl presents to her General Practice clinic with her mother, who is concerned as her daughter has been suffering from regular nosebleeds for her whole life. All nosebleeds have been self-ceasing with none requiring hospital admission. The girl has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. Her menarche occurred six months ago and since then she has had heavy periods, with bleeding lasting six days. On the heaviest day she needs to change pads every hour that are soaked through. This is resulting in her missing up to five days of school per month. The mother also comments that when her daughter had a tooth removed at age five, the dentist noted heavy bleeding during the procedure. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management following diagnostic testing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Factor VIII/vWF concentrate (Biostate)","Prothrombin Complex Concentrate (PCC)","Recombinant Factor VIII","Tranexamic Acid (TXA) and trial of Desmopressin (DDAVP)","Combined oral contraceptive pill"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIt is clear from the history that this patient is suffering from a significant bleeding disorder that is impacting her quality of life. Based on the history, the most likely diagnosis is von Willebrand disease (vWD) and the question focuses on the subsequent management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVon Willebrand disease is the most common inherited bleeding disorder, occurring in 1-2 % of the general population and clinically significant in a small proportion of this. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant fashion, but has variable clinical effects and penetrance. The main pathology is decreased or ineffective von Willebrand factor (vWF) which normally facilitates platelet adhesion as well as acts as a carrier for factor VIII and prevents its breakdown in the serum. Common presenting features include mucocutaneous bleeding (epistaxis, menorrhagia, easy bruising) and increased post-procedural bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are three possible management arms: antifibrinolytic treatment (\u003Cstrong\u003Etranexamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E), \u003Cstrong\u003Edesmopressin\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Efactor VIII/VWF concentrate\u003C/strong\u003E. Desmopressin triggers the release of stored endothelial vWF to increase serum concentrations. Importantly, patients need a monitored desmopressin challenge as some patients do not respond and it is generally most effective for type 1 VWD. Antifibrinolytics are useful for mild disease to decrease bleeding and can be used as an adjuvant to the two other therapies. Finally, factor VIII/VWF concentrate can be given but usually this is if desmopressin has failed or there is significant bleeding risk (pre-op for major surgery, previous significant bleeding such as GI bleeding). Therefore, this patient will most likely benefit from desmopressin and Tranexamic Acid in preference to factor VIII/VWF concentrate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn menorrhagia alone and in VWD, the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecombined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E has good evidence for symptom management but would not be first line or sole treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProthrombin Complex Concentrate (PCC),\u003C/strong\u003E such as Prothrombinex or Beriplex, is used to treat deficiencies of vitamin K dependent clotting factors (such as Warfarin reversal) and would not be appropriate in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecombinant Factor VIII\u003C/strong\u003E is used in the treatment of Haemophilia A. Given this is most likely a presentation of vWD, Factor VIII would not be the appropriate treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Von Willebrand disease (VWD) is the most common inherited bleeding disorder.","Management of VWD can include antifibrinolytic treatment (tranexamic acid), desmopressin or factor VIII/VWF concentrates."],"references":["Castaman G, Goodeve A, Eikenboom J. Principles of care for the diagnosis and treatment of von Willebrand Disease. Haematologica. 2013;98(5):667-674. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3640108/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88190"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2523"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88190"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-12T16:47:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-12T17:06:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2523"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105724"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"